.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInterestingly%2C%20some%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Forca-killer-whales-are-giant-dolphins-2023-5%5C%22%3Ewhale%20species%3C%2Fa%3E%20have%20also%20found%20ways%20to%20profit%20from%20the%20fishing%20business.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20not%20the%20money%20they're%20after%20%E2%80%94%20but%20the%20fish%20that%20outwit%20even%20the%20fishermen.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWhales%20discovered%20how%20to%20catch%20a%20free%20meal%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.in%2Fscience%2Fnews%2Fsperm-whales-taught-each-other-how-to-avoid-hunters-harpoons-200-years-ago-according-to-new-study%2Farticleshow%2F81604264.cms%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESperm%20whales%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20northern%20bottlenose%20whales%20off%20the%20coast%20of%20Newfoundland%20were%20observed%20time%20and%20again%20trailing%20fishing%20trawlers%20to%20catch%20the%20fish%20that%20escaped%20fishermen's%20nets.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20the%20whales%20didn't%20catch%20just%20any%20old%20fish.%20They%20were%20apparently%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffive-misconceptions-about-killer-whales-2023-5%5C%22%3Epicky%20eaters%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20only%20followed%20a%20vessel%20when%20it%20was%20fishing%20for%20Greenland%20halibut.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ENone%20of%20the%20whales%20that%20scientists%20observed%20pursued%20a%20trawler%20while%20it%20was%20catching%20redfish%2C%20thorny%20skate%2C%20or%20any%20other%20fish%20other%20than%20Greenland%20halibut.%20Scientists%20published%20their%20results%20in%20the%20journal%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0289626%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPLOS%20ONE%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20August.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222592%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Fish%20trawler%20net%20in%20the%20water.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64f0ba5157bff70019479496%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221944%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EFishermen%20nets%20are%20enormous%20and%20a%20whale%20can%20easily%20get%20caught%20in%20one%20accidentally%20if%20they%20venture%20too%20close.%3Cp%3EUsua%20Oyarbide%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhy-orcas-are-apex-predator-ocean-brain-scans-2023-5%5C%22%3Ewhales%20have%20learned%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20identify%20the%20fishing%20vessels%20as%20a%20source%20of%20easier%20fish%20to%20catch%2C%20reducing%20their%20time%20for%20foraging%2C%26quot%3B%20lead%20researcher%20Usua%20Oyarbide%20told%20Insider.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOyarbide%20first%20observed%20this%20behavior%20in%202007%20as%20part%20of%20her%20Master's%20thesis%20project.%20Then%20five%20to%20six%20years%20later%2C%20she%20said%20a%20fisherman%20sent%20her%20video%20of%20one%20of%20the%20same%20whales%20still%20chasing%20down%20fish.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20study%20isn't%20the%20first%20to%20report%20whale%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Forcas-beginning-whale-human-encounters-likely-to-rise-2023-7%5C%22%3Efishing%20boat%20encounters%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Scientists%20have%20found%20similar%20behavior%20among%20at%20least%2017%20other%20whale%20species%20in%20different%20parts%20of%20the%20world%20dating%20as%20far%20back%20as%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.biorxiv.org%2Fcontent%2F10.1101%2F2021.10.25.464263v4.full%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E1997%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Oyarbide%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20is%20a%20behavior%20that%20has%20been%20reported%20more%20and%20more%20over%20the%20past%2020%20years%20or%20so%2C%20in%20a%20number%20of%20parts%20of%20the%20world.%26quot%3B%20Hal%20Whitehead%2C%20a%20sperm%20whale%20expert%20and%20biology%20professor%20at%20Dalhousie%20University%2C%20told%20Insider.%20He%20wasn't%20involved%20in%20Oyarbide's%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhat's%20even%20more%20interesting%20is%20that%20it's%20not%20only%20whales%20that%20have%20learned%20to%20catch%20fish%20escaping%20the%20fishermen's%20nets.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223504%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Fish%20in%20the%20water%20after%20escaping%20a%20fish%20trawler's%20net.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64f0ba5857bff700194794af%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222336%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EBirds%20team%20up%20with%20the%20whales%20in%20hopes%20of%20catching%20a%20fish.%3Cp%3EUsua%20Oyarbide%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAs%20time%20goes%20on%20we%20hear%20more%20and%20more%20reports%20of%20everything%20from%20sperm%20whales%20to%20dolphins%20doing%20this.%20Probably%2C%20almost%20every%20species%20of%20marine%20mammals%20that%20eats%20fish%20somehow%20take%20advantage%20every%20now%20and%20then%20of%20a%20free%20meal%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Foceans.ubc.ca%2Fandrew-trites%2F%5C%22%3EAndrew%20Trites%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20director%20of%20the%20Marine%20Mammal%20Research%20Institute%20at%20the%20University%20of%20British%20Columbia%2C%20who%20also%20wasn't%20involved%20in%20the%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOyarbide%20further%20suggests%20that%20this%20behavior%20may%20become%20more%20common%20among%20whales%20in%20the%20future%20as%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.in%2Fscience%2Fnews%2Fwhales-can-learn-about-danger-and-can-warn-each-other-according-to-a-study-of-how-they-dodged-whaling-ships-in-the-19th-century%2Farticleshow%2F81949396.cms%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ewhales%20learn%20socially%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20each%20other%20and%20can%2C%20therefore%2C%20pass%20tips%20and%20tricks%20onto%20the%20next%20generation%2C%20and%20so%20on.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EIs%20it%20good%20for%20whales%20to%20follow%20fishing%20boats%3F%20No.%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EOyarbide%20said%20this%20change%20in%20whale%20behavior%20may%20seem%20beneficial%20for%20them%20at%20first%20as%20it%20increases%20their%20access%20to%20prey%20and%20reduces%20foraging%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20it%20can%20also%20make%20them%20more%20dependent%20on%20fish%20vessels%20for%20food%2C%20influencing%20their%20survival%20and%20reproduction.%20The%20whales%20likely%20began%20trailing%20trawlers%20because%20the%20boats%20overlapped%20their%20foraging%20areas%2C%20Oyarbide%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.in%2Fwere-accidentally-driving-this-extremely-ugly-fish-to-extinction%2Farticleshow%2F67524535.cms%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EOverfishing%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20such%20areas%20indirectly%20threatens%20the%20whales%20by%20decreasing%20the%20availability%20or%20altering%20the%20size%20or%20diversity%20of%20their%20prey.%20%26quot%3BIt%20is%20important%20to%20understand%20fisheries'%20impacts%20in%20marine%20ecosystems%2C%26quot%3B%20Oyarbide%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20issue%20is%20the%20%26quot%3Bhabitat%20degradation%20caused%20by%20bottom%20trawlers%20can%20have%20an%20indirect%2C%20negative%20impact%20on%20marine%20mammals%20that%20depend%20on%20those%20habitats%20for%20food%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222125%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Fishing%20boat%20in%20the%20evening.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64f0be1e57bff7001947997c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221411%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EFishing%20nets%20kill%20an%20estimated%20300%2C000%20marine%20mammals%20a%20year.%3Cp%3EVince%20Streano%20%2F%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%20of%20searching%20for%20food%2C%20some%20whales%20find%20it%20easier%20to%20catch%20prey%20just%20by%20following%20the%20trawlers.%20And%20that%20often%20leads%20to%20more%20risky%20interactions%20with%20vessels%20or%20fishing%20gear%2C%20Oyarbide%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20is%20probably%20bad%20for%20the%20whales%20in%20the%20long%20run%2C%26quot%3B%20Whitehead%20said.%20%26quot%3BThey%20sometimes%20get%20rammed%2C%20or%20shot%20by%20angry%20fishers%2C%20and%20can%20get%20caught%20in%20the%20nets.%20We%20saw%20a%20sperm%20whale%20killed%20by%20a%20trawler%20net%20close%20to%20the%20area%20mentioned%20in%20the%20study.%20They%20may%20also%20lose%20skills%20at%20catching%20their%20real%20food.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Forcas-full-of-forever-chemicals-substance-used-in-toilet-paper-2023-1%5C%22%3EFishing%20gear%20entanglement%3C%2Fa%3E%20alone%20causes%20the%20death%20of%20300%2C000%20whales%2C%20dolphins%2C%20and%20other%20cetacean%20mammals%20every%20year%2C%20according%20to%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fiwc.int%2Fmanagement-and-conservation%2Fentanglement%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EInternational%20Whaling%20Commission%3C%2Fa%3E.%20And%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.int-res.com%2Farticles%2Fesr2021%2F44%2Fn044p033.pdf%5C%22%3Estudy%3C%2Fa%3E%20published%20in%20January%20suggested%20this%20estimate%20was%20low.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMoreover%2C%20a%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fisheries.noaa.gov%2Ffeature-story%2Fnorth-atlantic-right-whales-and-dangers-vessel-strikes-and-entanglement%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereport%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20the%20National%20Oceanic%20and%20Atmospheric%20Administration%20suggests%20that%20females%20of%20the%20endangered%20North%20Atlantic%20right%20whale%20species%20are%20having%20fewer%20births%20because%20of%20stress%20and%20injuries%20from%20repeated%20fishing%20gear%20entanglements.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EOld%20observations%20can%20still%20teach%20something%20new%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThough%20Oyarbide%20is%20no%20longer%20researching%20whales%20and%20her%20observations%20in%20the%20study%20are%20many%20years%20old%2C%20Trite