re%20than%20three%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CIt%E2%80%99s%20not%20possible%20for%20me%20to%20describe%20what%20that%20felt%20like.%20Alone%20and%20scared%2C%20I%20was%20lucky%20to%20befriend%20three%20other%20children%20on%20the%20streets%20%E2%80%94%20a%20girl%20and%20her%20brothers.%20We%20would%20go%20looking%20for%20food%20together.%20We%20were%20so%20hungry%20all%20the%20time%2C%20that%20we%20would%20eat%20anything%20that%20we%20lay%20our%20hands%20on%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20adds.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAs%20she%20grew%20older%2C%20she%20had%20to%20be%20careful%20from%20the%20roving%20eyes%20and%20sexual%20advances%20by%20men.%20She%20recalls%20coiling%20in%20fear%20and%20sleeping%20behind%20old%20mattresses%20at%20shops%20for%20her%20safety.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CMen%20who%20were%20my%20father%E2%80%99s%20friends%20would%20touch%20me%20inappropriately.%20We%20used%20to%20feel%20scared%20whenever%20a%20man%20would%20pass%20by.%20Even%20my%20friend%E2%80%99s%20brothers%20were%20very%20afraid.%20We%20used%20to%20sleep%20behind%20some%20old%20mattresses%20at%20the%20scrap%20shop.%20We%20were%20always%20alert.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhen%20she%20was%20around%2011%20years%20old%2C%20she%20was%20rescued%20by%20an%20NGO.%20It%20was%20here%20that%20she%20received%20an%20education%20for%20the%20first%20time.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CSince%20I%20had%20never%20gone%20to%20school%2C%20they%20first%20gave%20me%20basic%20education.%20Next%20year%2C%20I%20took%20admission%20in%20Class%205.%20I%20was%20enjoying%20this%20normal%20life%20and%20loved%20going%20to%20school%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20adds.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EJust%20as%20things%20seemed%20to%20be%20going%20better%2C%20a%20call%20from%20her%20aunt%20sent%20life%20down%20another%20spiral.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CWhen%20I%20was%2013%2C%20my%20aunt%20called%20me%20home.%20The%20thought%20of%20going%20to%20family%20made%20me%20happy%20and%20she%20kept%20me%20well%20for%20a%20few%20da